social_posts.post_text: Closed today with a lovely buyer who I got into contract 6 days after meeting! I negotiated a seller credit to buy down her interest rate for the next two years. Flat roofs are prone to water intrusion because the only way for water to get off your roof is through a downspout — and if there’s too much rainfall, or your downspout is clogged, the standing water may penetrate the roofing material and get into your framing, bringing with it wood destroying organisms. Inspect your flat roof regularly, install flashing, maintain your gutters, and pre inspect with test holes before purchasing to be sure your framing isn’t damaged behind your siding.
So touched by this review. Thank you. This is what it’s all about

There’s no sheathing behind brick facade, and unfortunately the most intense seismic stress is at the perimeter of the home and low to the ground — right where a brick facade typically is. If you have a house with one of these low brick facades — common in 50s & 60s ranch houses here in Richmond, Oakland, and across the east bay — consider installing shear paneling in the interior to seismically reinforce your home 💪🏼

Concrete is made of rock aggregate and cement, which uses lime as a binding agent to essentially “glue” the concrete together. Efflorescence — white, powdery mineral deposit — is present to some degree on nearly every foundation, and is the salts in the cement (or sometimes the minerals in the soil *behind* the foundation) being leached to the surface by water running through the concrete. Excessive efflorescence means there’s likely insufficient drainage around the home, and if extreme eventually strips the concrete of its “glue”, leaving behind just rock aggregate which can crumble in your hands. This is just 1 of about a million reasons drainage is maybe the most important part of your home. I suggest that you use observation of efflorescence as another clue about the condition of your home! A good agent can help you uncover the whole story through observation, investigation and diligent inspection reading.

“Hi I’m under a house” is my tagline haha. 
Spalling, where concrete begins to crumble and break apart, is caused by too much water running through your foundation (insufficient drainage — my favorite topic). Severe spalling can weaken your foundation to the degree that it can no longer take seismic bolts. Drainage will save you so many problems, friends. It’s my number 1 recommendation to my clients, and will be a high yield upgrade when you decide to sell, in part because it will help maintain so many of the main systems of your home.

I can tell you this house was built in the 20s just by looking at the construction methods. One clue is the angle of the foundation wall. A battered (angled) foundation tells me this house is pre-WW2 and that the footing is poured very shallowly in the soil and that the concrete doesn’t contain rebar. Steel reinforcing bars (rebar) gives concrete tensile strength (strength when pulled apart). Foundations without rebar are more prone to cracking and movement, and at this point are nearing the end of their approx 100 serviceable life. Pre-WW2 concrete makes me very nervous because of the lack of rebar, the shallow footing and the often poor quality of the concrete mix. However, there’s ways to strengthen an old foundation without a total replacement (bolting, shear panels, and so forth).

I would never write an offer on nor list a flat roofed home without having test holes performed. I might consider it for a home with no overhangs if the home and pest inspections were performed by people I implicitly trusted, and if I had looked in the crawl space myself. This is an example of why an agent with structural knowledge is your greatest resource in your home search. A good agent with an understanding of basic building science, who knows what they’re looking at, how to spot structural issues, and what inspectors and tradespeople to call in to diagnose, can save you from nightmare situations like discovering $50,000 of water damage to the framing behind your siding AFTER you close on your new home. 

I always think about how when you buy a home you buy the roof, foundation, furnace, siding, etc. Did your agent help you to understand those systems in your house? Do you know their condition? This is why I practice real estate with a focus on education and construction. I want all my clients to have the confidence that they understand and can maintain the structure they’ve purchased. Your property is likely your biggest asset; be thoughtful in the agent you select to advise you.

TPO & composition shingle roofing — what are they, what’s their lifespan, and signs of aging in dimensional shingles

I really appreciate the support I receive on this page and I’m so glad my style of practicing real estate resonates with so many! This job is complex and truly never boring. We advise clients through an enormous financial acquisition, contending with contract law, ordinances across a number of municipalities, and a famously intense and competitive market. And chiefly, our product – our local houses – are by no means simple! Much of our housing stock is nearly 100 years old and comes with the litany of issues associated with that, and an added responsibility for a homeowner. But I adore our old houses, so I make a pointed effort to educate my clients about them; the construction, systems, and the maintenance of an old house, and what it means to be its steward – what that entails, what that costs, and how to know and understand the structure that you’re taking on as a home buyer in the Bay Area. 

I’m blessed and grateful to have a family in the trades (not to mention I am obsessive and annoyingly curious) so I am always learning more, exploring, climbing on a new roof and into a new crawlspace, opening up panels in every house I go into and always asking if I can see the attic.

There is much more to being a realtor than construction knowledge, but it’s a skill I wouldn’t practice real estate without. I am so lucky that my job is my true passion. And as always thank you for the trust.

This is a prefabricated shearwall, called a strong-wall, that resists lateral force in an earthquake and can ameliorate a soft story (living space over a weaker first floor, like a room above a garage — imagine the “pancaking” a structure like that can experience in an earthquake without proper seismic strengthening). Beautiful building innovation, so cool to see this on the job site today. @strongtie

GFCI outlets protect you from shock and are required within 6 ft of a basin — i.e. your kitchen and bathrooms and maybe a garage utility sink. If you’re relatively handy you can likely install em yourself for 5 bucks a pop from the hardware store. Let’s be responsible homeowners in 2024, I’m here to help 🫡

I was looking forward to this video because capillary action is such a cool way to see nature working… even though it can be to the detriment of our structures. But I love thinking about a tree pulling water up from the soil to hydrate itself. Anyway, this is the issue when we talk about a “faulty grade”. Nowadays siding stops 12” or more above the soil but if you have an older house with siding right to grade, protect your framing and don’t pile mulch and soil high against it. Pretty easy fix but the rain has a way of showing us our house’s weak spots!

Line wire stucco is a 50s/60s framing technique that I see all the time in the mid-century ranchers here in Richmond, El Cerrito and El Sobrante. Essentially the walls lack the shear value of wood sheathing or ply sheeting, which was installed in houses both before and after this period. Thankfully you can retrofit by installing plywood bracing at the interior either behind the Sheetrock or in an unfinished space like the garage, or at the exterior if you eventually re-side or re-stucco. 

I make videos like this so you, as a potential homebuyer, can be educated about, and knowledgeable of, the characteristics of the homes you consider purchasing. Houses of every era have their associated pros and cons — while the framing may be inferior in this era, I love the concrete, for example. My inbox is always open for questions and conversation because of course 90 seconds can’t cover this topic in its entirety!

I love heat pumps. I think they’re the future of HVAC. They both heat and cool, they’re space saving because the unit is outside and they don’t require ducts, they’re highly energy efficient, and you can have multiple climate zones throughout your house. This is a fantastic upgrade to make to a home when your furnace eventually dies.

My hot take is that asbestos is underrated!! I kid of course but before the toxic nature of asbestos was known it was widely used as a building material because of qualities like durability and rot resistance. Asbestos shingles are common here (I always notice them for their big rectangular shape and the kinda wavy border on the bottom that I think is supposed to emulate shingles). Sometimes there’s beautiful, salvageable redwood siding behind it. As a buyer, if you consider offering on a home with asbestos shingles that you eventually hope to remove, factor the expense of professional asbestos abatement into your projected renovation costs. And be sure to work with a diligent, construction-conscious and hyper-local agent when purchasing in the Bay Area, so you’re knowledgeable and educated about a home before writing an offer. 🫶🏼
